In looking at this, here's what I think needs to happen.

            if ( basicUsernamePassword.length==2 && encodedAccountUsername.length==2 ) {
              final String account = B64.standard.decString( encodedAccountUsername[1] );
              final String username = B64.standard.decString( encodedAccountUsername[0] );
              final String passwordSubstring = basicUsernamePassword[1];
              final String[] passwords = passwordSubstring.split( "@" , 2 );
              final String password = isChangePassword ? B64.standard.decString( passwords[0] ) : passwords[0]; 
              final String newPassword = ( passwords.length == 2 ) ? passwords[1] : null; 


The mistake is in always splitting that passwordSubstring. That should not be split UNLESS we're doing a change password!
My bad, I'm sure since I worked on this code. I can fix, but I'm not normally in a position to build and test new CLC code. Any volunteers? I can suggest a change. :-)

btw, simple change is;

replace:
             final String password = isChangePassword ? B64.standard.decString( passwords[0] ) : passwords[0]; 
with:
             final String password = isChangePassword ? B64.standard.decString( passwords[0] ) : passwordSubstring;

[~dkavanagh], your proposed fixed allowed users to log in. I a bit updated your fix. This is the diff I will merge to 3.3.1 as soon as I can:
{code}
-              final String password = isChangePassword ? B64.standard.decString( passwords[0] ) : passwords[0]; 
-              final String newPassword = ( passwords.length == 2 ) ? passwords[1] : null; 
+              final String password = isChangePassword ? B64.standard.decString( passwords[0] ) : passwordSubstring;
+              final String newPassword = ( isChangePassword && passwords.length == 2 ) ? passwords[1] : null;
{code}
